{"/service/ndnp/ndhi/batch_ndhi_jemhadar_ver01/data/sn85042243/00383346162/1937121601/0953.xml":{"full_text":"1\n4\njare\n51_JSUe,e Pl\u00bbyersare\ni\nTh*t\nThe Bismarck Tribune\nAn Independent Newspaper\nfHE STATE'S OLDEST NEWSPAPER\n(Established 1873)\n8tate, City and Count? Official Newspaper\nPublished dally except Sunday by The Bismarck mbune Company Bl\u00bb\nN. Di and entered at the postoffice at Bismarck as second class mall\nMrs. Stella 1. Mann\nPresident and Treasurer\nArchie O. Johnson Kenneth W Simons\nVie* Pres. and Gen'l. Manager Secretary and Editor\nSubscription Rates Payable in Advance\nDaily by carrier, per year 7.20\nDally by mall per yea. (in Bismarck) 7J0\nDally by mall per year (In state outside of Bismarck) 5.00\nDally by mall outside ot North Dakota 6.00\nWeekly by mall In statt. per year 1.00\nWeekly by mall outside ot North Dakota, per year 1.50\nWeekly by mall In Canada, per year 3.00\nMember of Audit Bureau of Circulation\nMember of the Associated Press\nThe Associated Press is exclusively entitled to the use for republica\ntion of the news dispatches credited to It or not otherwise credited in this\nnewspaper and also the local news of spontaneous origin published herein.\nAll rights of republication of all other matter herein are also reserved.\nU. S. Had Conscience as Dollar Diplomat\nThere may not seem to be much connection between a\ncrowd of angry U. S. marines wrecking a newspaper office in\nNicaragua and a calm discussion of the problem of imperialism\nin the modern world. But a cablegram from Central America\nlinked the two very neatly, the other day, and provided a little\nnourishing food for thought.\nAway back in 1922, or thereabouts, our marines were sta\ntioned in Nicaragua. A stout Nicaraguan patriot, Dr. Buitrago\nDiaz, objected bitterly. In his newspaper, the Tribuna, at\nManagua, he put the marines on the pan and said contemptu\nously that they were unfit for the companionship of the women\nof Nicaragua.\nSome of the marines could read Spanish. So one day a\nbunch of the lads got together and made a raid on the Tribuna's\noffices, wrecking them with a hearty thoroughness such as only\ninfuriated marines can achieve.\nAnd the wind-up of the story came just the other day,\nwhen a United States treasury check covering the damages was\nhanded toljr. Diaz.\nWell, so what? Does that prove anything in particular,\nexcept that Uncle Sam does pay his bills if you give him time\nenough?\nYou can appreciate the story best if you reflect on the\nthings that have been said about America's land-grabbing\nexploits.\nIn the last few years Americans have waxed indignant\nabout Mussolini's seizure of Ethiopia, Japan's attack on China,\nand so on\u2014and have been told that they had no right to\nthrow stones because Uncle Sam himself expanded his terri\ntorial holdings by force, with Latin-Americans, Indians and\nother luckless people paying the freight.\nBut there is a little difference there, somehow, and this\nNicaraguan story does illustrate it.\nClumsily, often tardily, generally somewhat inadequately,\nthis country has made an effort to redress the balance. The\nmarines are out of Nicaragua now, the country is free and inde\npendent\u2014and even a minor bit of \"aggression\" like the mob\nscene in the newspaper office is at last paid for by the U. S.\n.treasury.\nMexico did get the cash of the Gadsden purchase\u2014and two\ndecades later, got the French lifted off her neck by orders from\nWashington. Spain did get a lump sum for the Philippines,\nand Cuba actually did go free. The government has spent some\nmillions of dollars caring for the dispossessed Indians. Alaska\nwas acquired by straight purchase. The old marines-have\nlanded era of \"dollar diplomacy\" did finally end.\nThat record could be a great deal better\u2014but it could also\nbe a great deal worse.\nIt is not exactly the sort of record a greedy and ruthless\npeople would make. Greed is in it, of course\u2014but it is tempered\nby conscience, after all.\nForeign militarists engaged in stealing the lands of weaker\npeoples will have to look a little farther to find justification for\ntheir actions.\nStill in the Red\nThe difficulties which meet an administration that tries to\nbalance its budget in a time of increasing industrial stagnation\namply illustrated by the announcement at Washington that\n\u202223,000,000-a-month increase in WPA spending has been\n|ordered to cope with unemployment.\nTwenty-three millions a month constitute heavy spending,\neven in a government like ours. Since relief expenditures have\nbeen one of the main reasons for the unbalanced budget, it is\nbard to see how the budgetlbalancing act is going to be accom\nplished when relief costs are going up at that rate.\nYet what is to be done? The need exists. Unemployment\njig Indisputably on the rise. Something has to be done, and the\nfederal government is the only agency that can do it.\nIn the long run, a balanced budget must wait on full business\nrevival. Until that revival comes, government accountants will\nhave to keep the jug of red ink handy.\nAlimony Absurdity\nIt is a little bit hard to work up a whole lot of sympathy\nor indignation over the lot of either party to a divorce suit,\nbecause the troubles which arise in divorce court are troubles\nwhich people bring on themselves. Nevertheless, the matter\njof alimony does occasionally call for a little straightforward\ndenouncing.\nIn Connecticut, for instance, a lady who is suing for divorce\ndemands alimony of $1,000 a month pending trial of the suit.\nHer husband objects, saying that her income is $45,000 a year\nand she does not need the alimony. She replies that he is mis\ntaken last year her income was a scant $30,000.\nA case like that makes one wonder why we continue to\n\u2022\u2022put up with the institution of alimony at all, except in cases\nwhere there are children to support. For this seems to be the\nreduction ad absurdum of the idea that an able-bodied woman\n\u2022to entitled to fat sums from a man simply because she once\naccorded him the privilege of supporting her.\nmerely trying to maintain the Old Heidelberg\ntraditions, and all they ask Is something a little better In fellowships.\ni\nSenator Capper proposes a federal statute on marriage and divorce\u2014\npM If enough wives weren't already laying down the law.\n1\nf. the public gets set for a pleasant little business cycle, it\n^.fURM Into the old variety of tall spin.\ni\nll-mooth-year advocate turns up again in California at an ln\nImhIoii\ncongress with time on his\ni: aon-ln-law by divorce, the oon practical students\nsmumlng that relativity remains a theory.\nRussia ought to humanise its propaganda\u2014for Instance,\nbaa done to\ndmml\nIt\nScenes\nBehiti!t\nWashington\nInsiders Think New Deal May Start\nSpending Again to Cure Depression\nFight Expected on Firearms\nAct Changes.\nBy RODNEY DUTCHER\n(Tribune Washington Correspondent)\nWashington, Dec. 18.\u2014Some of the\nmost Important members of the ad\nministration's Inside group are now\nconvinced that only an Increase in\ngovernment spending will snap the\nnation out of depression. They are\nsure the New Deal will \"start spend\ning again\" in the near future.\nThe prediction comes from men\nwho usually know in advance what\nPresident Roosevelt is got.g to pro\npose, although It Is not yet being\nwhispered that the President him'\nself actually has concluded\nthat\nthere's no hope for resumption of\nrecovery except through spending.\nThe drive for a private house\nbuilding boom and such co-operation\nand concessions as the administra\ntion Is offering to business are ex\npected to help. But there Is no indi\ncation that private enterprise is gO'\ning to be able to check the eco\nnomic spiral and that means, a&\n'Berry Here? So\nWhat?*\nAfter Senator George Berry of\nTennessee, labor leader and would\nbe peacemaker between the C. I. O.\nand A. F. of L., had visited cham\nbers outside the room where Wil\nliam Green and John Lewis were\nconferring, assistants to the con\nferees hastened to offer newspa\npermen an official version of the\nBerry call.\nSenator Berry, it was said, had\nasked that the conferees be ad\nvised that he had arrived. The\nconferees were Lewis, Green,\nChairman Philip Murray of the\nSteel Workers' Organizing Com\nmittee and President George M.\nHarrison of the Brotherhood of\nRailway Clerks. Ralph Hetzel, sec\nretary to Lewis, went inside to\nbreak the news that Berry was\noutside.\nNarrators of the official ver\nsion admit that Lewis raised his\neyebrows but say that the group\nremained silent and unimpressed.\nThe unofficial version of the in\ncident, however, insists that one\nmember of the quartet asked: \"So\nwhat?\"\nAt any rate, Senator Berry dldnt\nleave without posing for the news\nreels and making\na\nstatement.\ncording to insiders, that the job can\nbe done only by pumping mora gov\nernment funds into the economic sys\ntem.\nGovernment spending machinery\nhas been kept well oUed with that\npossible eventuality, which seems in\ncreasingly probable, in view.\nIf\nthose who now\nthey usually are\npredict a new\nspending program are as\naccurate as\nIn their prophecies,\nthe government\ndebt is in for another\nsizable boost.\nWill Fight Over Firearms\nAttorney General Homer S. Cam\u00ad\nming* and lobbyists for munitions in\nterests are girding for a fight which\nwill come when \"the A. G.\" presents\nhis proposed amendments to the Na\ntional Firearms Act.\nEspecially bitter opposition\nhearings.\nwill\nbe\nregistered against a proposal that\nany man buying a gun be required to\nfurnish his fingerprints. Cummlngs\ncontends that any honest man\nwould\nbe willing to give his fingerprints,\nbut that a crook would not, and\nhence wouldn't get a gun.\nThere's a small clique of lobbyists\nwhich always appears at any state\ncapital or In the national\ncapital\nwhenever a firearms bill is proposed.\nDepartment of justice officials can\nrattle off a list of about a dozen names\nof persons sure to be on hand if and\nwhen Cummlngs' bill comes\nup\nfor\nHere's How It's Pronounced\nInternational Secretary G. M. Bug\nniazet of the Brotherhood of Elec\ntrical Workers has been somewhat in\nthe news lately, especially as a con\nferee at some of\nthe AFL-CIO meet\nings.\nmay be helpful, for conversa\ntional purposes,\nto report that Bug\nniazet's\nname is pronounced \"boon\nya-zet.\"\n(Copyright,\n1937, NBA Service, Inc.)\nBARBS\nThe crusading politician who is al\nways about to \"name names\" rarely\ngets any farther than calling them.\nMichigan police have a device that\nreads palms of suspects. Its greatest\nvalue Is expected to be in locating\nfinger\" men.\nNazi magicians ordered not to use\nedibles in their tricks are now liter\nally pulling them out of hats.\nA film writer complains he wrote\nsteadily for six months on\na\nscenario\nwhich was not used. Plainly,\na\nof all work and no play.\ncase\nIstanbul treats Itself to a big show\nof military power. Maybe the natives\nare afraid Turkey may become an\nInternational dish.\nSoviets are planning to extend\ntheir Arctic explorations in spite of\nthe fact that the average Pole doesn't\napprovf.\nGermany has succeeded in making\nsynthetic eggs from fish and Nails\nare looking forward to some fine\nbreakfasts of poached herring.\nFew tears were shed in the stove\nleague this fall because the Dust Bowl\ngame was called on account of the\nweather.\nThe big boom everyone was expect\ning came from China, and it wasnt\nmade by a firecracker.\nThe man who dived\ntune\nwhat the\n430 feet\nif\nin\nMichigan and came up\nLake\nalive has a for\u00ad\nhe can\nadapt his equipment to\nstock plunging.\nThe woman writer's husband who\nsued for divorce claimed she expected\nhim to exist on a diet of dry serials.\nDora thinks the garment workers'\nunion ought to be reminded of some\nof the slaves who art spending thell\nlives in Hollywood making shorts.\nThe Great Game o\nC\u00abtrrltM lasr, kr The Balttam\nTHE MELLON VINDICATION\nIt, of course, makes no difference\nto Mr. Mellon now, but It does seem\nthat the administration officials re\nsponsible for the criminal proceedings\nagainst him, recently declared wholly\nunfounded by the United States Board\nof Tax Appeals, would want to make\nsome sort of public apology before the\nwhole episode Is forgotten.\nNaturally, it is too late to be of any\nbenefit to Mr. Mellon, but one would\nthink that their own self-respect would\nmake some sort of gesture Imperative.\nIt isn't necessary to have been an ad\nmirer of Mr. Mellon's, either person\nally, or politically, a \"creature of Wall\nStreet\" or a member of the bungling\nold Liberty League, to feel indigna\ntion at the sort of thing attempted\nagainst him and which, after three\nyears of testimony and argument, has\nnow been labeled \"entirely unjusti\nfiable\" by a commission which, If\nprejudiced at all, certainly would not\nbe prejudiced In his favor.\nIt is almost impossible to read the\nrecord in this extraordinary case with\nout concluding that the real motive\nback of It was political. The charge\nwas made that Mr. Mellon had at\ntempted to defraud the government.\nIn effect, branding him as a tax dodger\nand a crook, the attorney general,\nsupported by the, secretary of the\ntreasury, tried to secure a criminal\nindictment from a grand jury. It was\ncharged by Mr. Mellon\u2014and the facts\nbore out the charge\u2014that he was not\naccorded the same treatment as other\nA\nBIT OF HUMOR\nNOW AND THEN\nIS RELISHED ST\nTHE BEST OF MEN\nLew (admiringly)\u2014You know, you're\nnot such a bad-looking girl.\nWanda (simperlngly) Now, Lew,\nyou'd say so even if you didn't think\nso.\nLew Fifty-fifty, old girl. You'd\nthink so even if I didn't say so.\nXmas Shopper But this talking\ndoll won't talk.\nBright Clerk\u2014No, I'm sorry. You\nsee, it's supposed to belong to the dip\nlomatic service.\nChristy\u2014What sort of a chap Is\nJack?\nMary\u2014Well, he was over to see me\nlast night and when the lights went\nout he spent the rest of the evening\ntrying to repair them.\nBoogy I can see good in every\nthing.\nWoogy\u2014Can you see good In the\ndark?\nMeeker Your honor, she's been\nthrowing things at me ever since we\nwere married 20 years ago.\nJudge Sockman\u2014Then why havent\nyou complained before?\nMeeker\u2014This is the first time she's\nhit me, your honor.\nI SO THEY SAY I\nThere Is a new form of slavery here.\nI mean slavery to business.\u2014Sinclair\nLewis, novelist.\nHie Red Army is for peace, but we\nare ready to beat off any enemy at\ntack.\u2014Marshal Klementi Voroshlloff,\nMoscow.\nA gentle pat on the cheek and a\nlight squeeze of the hand Is very help\nful.\u2014Dr. Ansel Chine, Tulane Univer\nIsty medical school, advising nurses.\nIt's beautiful.\u2014Julian Gallndo, 12,\nof El Paso, Texas, after an operation\non his eyes which permitted him to\nsee for the first time.\nMany boys are too shy to make\ndates parent* should step in and en\ncourage them.\u2014Rev. Dr. Roy Burk\nhart, Columbus, Ohio.\n-*Aj\u00ab ^,v.\u201e\nTHE BISMARCK TRIBUNE, THURSDAY, DECEMBER 16.1937\nThe 4-Point Express Seems to Be Stuck\ntaxpayers and to which be Was entitled\nunder the rules. The usual notice of\ndeficiency was not given him, he had\nno chance to file a protest and was not\naccorded a hearing. \"I want,\" said Mr.\nMellon on May 4,1934, \"no adjustment\nof my taxes not entirely within my\nlegal rights. But, most Important of\nall, I want an end to the long cam\npaign of villlflcation that has been\ncarried on and my name cleared of\nthe unwarranted charges the attor\nney general has brought against me.\"\nOn another occasion he said, \"I would\nrather spend my remaining days in\njail than submit to such tyranny.\"\nIhough the grand jury refused to\nindict Mr. Mellon and the government\nhad to drop Its criminal charges, it\npursued to the bitter end its case for\nthe recovery of more than $3,000,000 in\ntaxes claimed. Now, three months\nafter his death and three years after\nthe charges were made, the govern\nment's own tribunal vindicates Mr.\nMellon of any fraudulent Intent and\nreduces the amount of taxes in ques\ntion to $700,000\u2014and that is disputed.\nThe real point is that he is acquitted\nwholly of any suspicion of dishonesty,\nand that Is the thing that ought to\nmake the men who emphasised the\ncriminal side of the charges feel\nashamed. Certainly, neither the at\ntorney general nor the secretary\" of\nthe treasury can be proud of the part\nthey ha\"d in this persecution. It was\nevident to every discriminating per\nson at the time that the criminal\ncharges against Mr. Mellon fitted in\nwith the administration political\nstrategy of arousing class feeling in\nthe country. And It should have been\nevident to everyone able to think at\nall that even If Mr. Mellon were utter\u00ad\nfl\nPOLITICS\nMdKemegr om BirMge\nVICTORY CUE IN DISCARDS\n*A63\nV A 43\nA K\nAccurate Count Shows Declarer the Correct Play to Gather In\nNeeded Trick for Four Spades\nBy WILLIAM E. McKENNEY\n(Secretary, American Ceotwact Bridge\nToday's hand looks fairly simple at\nfirst glance. With spades as tfumps.\nNorth has no spade or heart losers,\nand In addition can take three tricks\nSOLUTION TO PREVIOUS\nCONTRACT PROBLEM\n,*KQJM\n\u00a56\n1052\n4b Q10 IS\nW\n*\u202275\nQ10 9 8\n\u00a5KJ5\nQJf\nS7\u00ab4\nDealer\n4AJI4\nK632\nDuplicate\u2014N. S. vuL\nWest North\n1\u00ab Pass A\n2N.T. Pass 3*\n3* Pass 4*\nOpening lead\u2014# Q. 1\u00ab\nin diamonds and hearts with high\ncardi.\nAll that he needs Is to be able to\ndevelop two club tricks, but that is\nnot as easy as It might appear at\nfirst glance.\nTift opening lead of the diamond\nqueen was won in dummy with the\nking. Three rounds of trumps were\ntaken. West discarding a diamond on\nthe third lead.\nA club was then led toward the king\nin dummy which held the trick. A\nclub was returned, hoping for a three'\ntwo spUt in that suit, but West failed\nto follow and an immediate change\nof plan was necessary if the contract\nwas to be made. Declarer played the\neight of clubs, Bast winning with ttoi\nnine.\nBy FRANK R. KENT\nly destitute of deoency, be would\nhardly be fool enough to be dishonest\nabout his Income tax.\nTo believe that an 80-year-old man,\nwho was busy giving away millions of\ndollars and who had so many millions\nthat they bad ceased to have any\nmeaning for him, Would stoop to that\nkind of stupidity was to believe that\nhe and his lawyers were not only\ncrooked but crasy. Yet the fact is that\nbecause of the administration propa\nganda and ballyhoo is presenting the\ncharges, undoubtedly a good many\nunthinking people did think Mr. Mel\nIon guilty.\nNow that his innocence has been\nofficially established one would think\nthat the officials who made the crim\ninal charge might want to say some\nthing in justification of this shocking\nbusiness if there is anything to say.\nOr that the president might. Only\nthe completely credulous believe that\nthe attorney general, a notoriously\ncautious man, would have launched\nso dramatic an attack without the\napproval of his chief. It Just isn't\ndone. Perhaps there are those who\nexpected from the president some\nexpression of gratification that Mr.\nMellon's reputation has been cleared.\nBut neither from him nor from any\none connected with him has come such\na word. It has been ten days since\nthe decision was made and no word\nhas come. Obviously now none ever\nwill come. Asked last week at his\npress conference* if he had anything\nto say about the vindication of Mr.\nMellon, Mr. Roosevelt said, \"I havent\nread the board's decision.\" That's all.\nFor sheer callousness the whole per\nformance la without a parallel.\nA heart was returned, which dummy\nwon with the ace. Declarer now saw\nthat his chance to make the hand\nwaa to force Bast to lead either dia\nmonds or clubs to him.\nNorth now played a small heart,\nruffing in his own hand, Bast's jack\nfalling. Dummy was re-entered with\nthe ace of diamonds and another\nheart ruffed, Bast dropping the king.\nDeclarer now knew that East held\nprobably the diamond Jade (as he had\nopened the queen) and the ace and\njack of clubs.\nStaking the result en the accuracy\nof this count, the diamond 10 was\nled, and Bast, after winning, could do\nnothing but cash the ace of clubs and\nconcede the last trick to the club\nqueen In declarer's hand.\nContract Problem\nla\nAt a contract of ibree no\ntrump, eight cold tricks are\nvisible but North may have a\nproblem to develop the ninth.\n4X114\nVAKSS\n*X(I\nYour\n\u2022aee or aiar\nIn car* of The Tribune.\n\u00abe!f-addr*M*d envelope.\nGermany.\n12 Imbecile.\n13 Electrified\nparticle.\n14 Winged.\n16 To yelp.\n17 To peruse.\n15 Previously.\n19 Not wet\n20 Obese.\n21 Arrived.\n22 3.1416\n23 Exists.\n24 Short cask.\n25 Too.\n26 Chum.\n27 Skillet.\n28 To turn\ntoward the\neast\n29 In order\n31 To slide.\n32 To scatter.\n33 Girl.\n34 Before Christ\nAJ102\n\u00bb76\n\u00ab986\n4Q1098\nQJ107\nr_\n*\u202276\nvqios\n\u2022'-\u2022AK*'\n\u2022A764\nDuplicate\u2014N. It S. vuL\nOpener\u2014\u2022 J.\n(Oopgrright, 1*37, MBA Servta*, IncJ\nPersonal Health\nBy William Brady, M. D.\nDr. Brady will answer questions pertaining te health kit aet 41s\nor diajrnoela. Write letters briefly and in ink. Address Dr. Brady\nAll queries most be accompanied by\na\nNERVOUS EXHAUSTION AND BRAIN FAG\nProfessor Benedict determined by scientific measurement that one-half\nof a salted peanut or a cracker provides sufficient energy to supply the re\nquirement of a brain doing intense mental work for an hour or more.\nRecent observations by physiologists indicate that the most suitable\nenergy or fuel for the nerve cells and brain cells is sugar, carbohydrate that\nuse of this fuel by the nerve cells and brain cells produces more or less lactic\nacid as a by-product and that this acid by-product of metabolism or func\ntioning of nerves and brain, comparatively small though It be In quantity\n(compared, that is, with the lactic acid produced by muscular exercise, play\nor work), accounts for nerve fatigue or brain fag.\nHave anther piece of candy or a sundae, ma'am, and pipe down on your\nexacting domestic and social cares.\nMore oxygen, to oxidise or bum up the lactic add, is the antidote or\nremedy for nervous fatigue or brain fag.\nWhat, belly breathing? Well, that would help In many cases. But, as\nwe have pointed out repeatedly, you cant hoist yourself by lifting on your\nown bootstraps. The belly breathing exercise Increase the absorption of oxy\ngen only a wee bit\u2014a# much aa any other muscular exercise of similar degree\nand duration does. General exercise is the best way to Increase the absorp\ntion of oxygen.\nTwo miles of oxygen on the hoof is an excellent remedy for nervous fa\ntigue or brain fag\u2014a better remedy than sitting or lying at rest or sleeping.\nIf the big shots In the business, Industrial and professional worlds and the\nwomen who become too deeply engrossed In domestic and social Interests\nhad to do three to six miles on the hoof every day, we'd hear a great deal\nless about nervous breakdown\u2014both\nTrll\u00bbu*/tT'g\nHOLD EVERYTHING!\nmimmim\n\"But I DIDNT tell your wife what time you came in I 1\njust said 1 was too busy getting breakfast to notice.\"\nAn Ex-Emperor\nHORIZONTAL Answer to Previous Pnsle\n1 Former\nemperor of\nCHESS\ndepression in\nthe cheek.\n40 Dower\nproperty.\n41 To apportion\ncards.\n42 Saclike cavity\n44 Dispatched.\n45 To debate.\n46 Demigoddess\nof fate.\n51 He was also\nking of\n35 Electrical unit. 52 The World\n36 Grit War\n27 Blue grass. during, his\n38 Slight reign.\n51He\nstamped.\nterms.\nPhysiologists have for many years assumed the existence of a catalyst in\nthe blood and tissues which governs or controls oxidation. The amount of\noxidation going on in the oells or tissues does not depend on the quantity of\noxygen absorbed, or on the quantity in the blood. The nature of this catalyst\nor ensyme is not clearly determined but most physiologists at present recog\nnise that some such agent Is essential for normal oxidation.\nForgive me for interjecting here the crasy notion (my own) that vitamins\nmay have something to do with the oxidation process, especially vitamin B.\nCertainly vitamin Is essential for the normal metabolism of carbohydrate.\nMany readers have Informed me that a few months after they have adopted\nthe practioe of suple men ting their diet with a daily ration of vitamins B,\nand they no longer feel the nervous fatigue, brain fag or'weakness that\nformerly handicapped them.\nQUESTIONS AND ANSWERS\nEidaiged Tbyaras\nAt IS months cur daughter bad enlarged thymus, shown by Xray treat\nments given. At age of three yean, picture showed no enlargement left.\nWould It be safe to give her ether for tonsil operation? (Mrs. F. J. M.)\nAnswer\u2014X-ray film shows enlarged thymus in not a few infants or\nyoung children who are perfectly normal. Regardless of the thymus, I sug\ngest that you first try giving the child an optimal ration of vitamin to\nsupplement bar diet for six months. If the tooell hypertrophy does not\ndisappear by early summer, then consider tbe operation.\n(Copyright, 1937, John F. Dille Co.)\nClyde llewlg\nin\nHolland.\n17 Taxi.\n18 To relieve.\n20 Merriment\n21 To snip.\n22 Butter lump.\n24 Marble used\nas a shooter.\n25 Dry.\n26 Parent\n27 Seed bag.\n28 Fetid.\n30 Resident\n31 Wise.\n33 Shaded walk.\n34 Political\ndictator.\n36 Gaiters.\n37 Harbors.\n39 Billot fare.\n40 Instrumental\nduet.\n42 Feather scarf.\n43 Data.\n44 Spain.\n45 Musical note.\n47 Either.\n48 Right\n49 Northeast,\n50 Paid publicity\nVERTICAL\n1 Knots in wood\n2 Breezy.\nSKind.\n4 Southeast\n5 Tumultuous\ndisturbance.\nWa* victorious\n7 Within,\nInstrument\n9\nOtherwise.\n.10 Upright shaft\nMountain.\n2 after\nthe war's end.\n15 He lives in\n1","height":"27216","width":"